Arbatsko-Pokrovskaya Line.label: Arbatsko-Pokrovskaya Line
Arbatsko-Pokrovskaya Line.description: The Arbatsko–Pokrovskaya Line is one of the lines of the Moscow Metro. Chronologically the second to open, it connects the district of Mitino and the town of Krasnogorsk to the northwest of Moscow with ... Wikipedia

Chūō Main Line.label: Chūō Main Line
Chūō Main Line.description: The Chūō Main Line, commonly called the Chūō Line, is one of the major trunk railway lines in Japan. Wikipedia

Kaluzhsko-Rizhskaya Line.label: Kaluzhsko-Rizhskaya Line
Kaluzhsko-Rizhskaya Line.description: The Kaluzhsko–Rizhskaya Line is a line of the Moscow Metro, that originally existed as two separate radial lines, Rizhskaya and Kaluzhskaya opened in 1958 and 1962, respectively. Wikipedia

East Coast Main Line.label: East Coast Main Line
East Coast Main Line.description: The East Coast Main Line is a 393-mile long high-speed railway link between London, Peterborough, Doncaster, Wakefield, Leeds, York, Darlington, Newcastle, Edinburgh and is electrified along the whole route. Wikipedia

Ländchesbahn.label: Ländches Railway
Ländchesbahn.description: The Ländches Railway is a single non-electrified branch railway line between Wiesbaden and Niedernhausen, Germany. The 19.6-kilometre long line was opened in July 1879 by the Hessian Ludwig Railway. Wikipedia

Lyublinsko-Dmitrovskaya Line.label: Lyublinsko-Dmitrovskaya Line
Lyublinsko-Dmitrovskaya Line.description: Lyublinsko-Dmitrovskaya Line is the line of the Moscow Metro. It was known as "Lyublinskaya Line" before 2007. First opened in 1995 as a semi-chordial radius it is at present in process of being extended through the centre and northwards. Wikipedia

Chemins de fer du Jura.label: Chemins de fer du Jura
Chemins de fer du Jura.description: The Chemins de fer du Jura, the railways of the Jura canton in northern Switzerland, came about as the result of an amalgamation, in 1944, of four independent companies connecting Porrentruy to Bonfol, ... Wikipedia

Northeast Corridor.label: Northeast Corridor
Northeast Corridor.description: The Northeast Corridor is a fully electrified railway line that serves the Northeast megalopolis of the United States. Owned primarily by Amtrak, it runs from Boston through New York City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore to Washington, D.C. Wikipedia

Palatine Maximilian Railway.label: Palatine Maximilian Railway
Palatine Maximilian Railway.description: The Palatine Maximilian Railway - sometimes referred to as Maximiliansbahn or just the Maxbahn - is a railway line in southwestern Germany that runs from Neustadt an der Weinstrasse to Wissembourg in ... Wikipedia

Skitube Alpine Railway.label: Skitube Alpine Railway
Skitube Alpine Railway.description: The Skitube Alpine Railway is a standard gauge electric rack railway in the Kosciuszko National Park in New South Wales, Australia. It provides access to the snowfields at Blue Cow Mountain and the Perisher Valley. Wikipedia

Radebeul–Radeburg railway.label: Radebeul–Radeburg railway
Radebeul–Radeburg railway.description: The Radebeul–Radeburg railway, also known as the Lößnitzgrundbahn and locally nicknamed the Lößnitzdackel, is a 750 mm gauge narrow gauge steam-hauled railway in the outskirts of Dresden, Germany. Wikipedia

Tagansko-Krasnopresnenskaya Line.label: Tagansko-Krasnopresnenskaya Line
Tagansko-Krasnopresnenskaya Line.description: The Tagansko-Krasnopresnenskaya is the busiest line of the Moscow Metro. Built in 1966-1975 and extended in 2013, it cuts Moscow on a northwest-southeast axis and contains 21 stations. Wikipedia

Tama Toshi Monorail Line.label: Tama Toshi Monorail Line
Tama Toshi Monorail Line.description: The Tama Toshi Monorail Line, also referred to as the Tama Monorail, is an important part of the Western Tokyo public transport network. Wikipedia

Tokyo Metro Chiyoda Line.label: Tokyo Metro Chiyoda Line
Tokyo Metro Chiyoda Line.description: The Tokyo Metro Chiyoda Line is a rapid transit line owned and operated by Tokyo Metro in Tokyo, Japan. Wikipedia

Zamoskvoretskaya Line.label: Zamoskvoretskaya Line
Zamoskvoretskaya Line.description: Zamoskvoretskaya Line, formerly Gorkovsko-Zamoskvoretskaya, is a line of the Moscow Metro. Opened in 1938, chronologically it became the third line. Wikipedia

Washington Metro.label: Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority
Washington Metro.description: The Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority is a tri-jurisdictional government agency that operates transit service in the Washington Metropolitan Area. Wikipedia

LGV Atlantique.label: LGV Atlantique
LGV Atlantique.description: The LGV Atlantique is a high-speed railway line running from Paris to Western France. It opened in 1989-1990. It divides into two parts at Courtalain, one going westward to Le Mans, the second one going southwestward to Tours. Wikipedia

LGV Rhône-Alpes.label: LGV Rhône-Alpes
LGV Rhône-Alpes.description: The LGV Rhône-Alpes is a 115 km-long French high-speed rail line situated in the Rhône-Alpes region which extends the LGV Sud-Est southwards. Wikipedia

Gospel Oak to Barking Line.label: Gospel Oak to Barking Line
Gospel Oak to Barking Line.description: The Gospel Oak to Barking Line is part of the London Overground network of railway lines, connecting Gospel Oak in North London and Barking in East London. Wikipedia

Northern City Line.label: Northern City Line
Northern City Line.description: The Northern City Line is a railway line from Moorgate to Finsbury Park in London, part of the Great Northern Route services. Wikipedia

Mont Blanc Tramway.label: Mont Blanc Tramway
Mont Blanc Tramway.description: The Mont Blanc Tramway or Tramway du Mont-Blanc is a mountain railway line in the Haute-Savoie department of France. It is the highest in France and among the highest in Europe. Wikipedia

Serpukhovsko-Timiryazevskaya Line.label: Serpukhovsko-Timiryazevskaya Line
Serpukhovsko-Timiryazevskaya Line.description: Serpukhovsko–Timiryazevskaya Line, sometimes colloquially referred to as Grey Line, is a line of the Moscow Metro. Originally opened in 1983, it was extended throughout the 1980s and early 90s and again in the early 2000s. Wikipedia

West London Line.label: West London Line
West London Line.description: The West London Line is a short railway in inner West London that links Clapham Junction in the south to Willesden Junction in the north. It has always been an important cross-London link especially for freight services. Wikipedia

Berlin Nord-Süd Tunnel.label: Berlin Nord-Süd Tunnel
Berlin Nord-Süd Tunnel.description: The North–South S-Bahn Tunnel is a section of the Berlin S-Bahn under the city centre. The title North–South Tunnel is also used for the new Tiergarten Tunnel, part of the North–South main line used by intercity and regional trains. Wikipedia

Greyhound Canada.label: Greyhound Canada
Greyhound Canada.description: Greyhound Canada is the prominent operator of inter-city coach services in Canada. Greyhound Canada is a subsidiary of Scotland's FirstGroup plc, linked with Dallas-based Greyhound Lines. Wikipedia

Mannar Line.label: Mannar Line
Mannar Line.description: The Mannar Line is a railway line in Sri Lanka. Branching off the Northern Line at Medawachchiya Junction, the line heads north-west through North Central and Northern provinces before terminating at the town of Talaimannar. Wikipedia

Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway.label: Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway
Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway.description: The Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway was a common carrier railroad that later became an operating subsidiary of the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway in Arizona. Wikipedia

Winterthur–Etzwilen railway line.label: Winterthur–Etzwilen railway line
Winterthur–Etzwilen railway line.description: The Winterthur–Etzwilen railway line is a railway line in Switzerland. It links Winterthur in the canton of Zurich with Etzwilen in the canton of Thurgau. Wikipedia

Andal-Sainthia Branch Line.label: Andal–Sainthia branch line
Andal-Sainthia Branch Line.description: The Andal–Sainthia branch line is a railway line connecting Andal on the Bardhaman–Asansol section of the Howrah–Delhi Main Line and Sainthia Junction on the Sahibganj Loop. This 73 kilometres track is under the jurisdiction of Eastern Railway. Wikipedia

Coudekerque-Branche–Fontinettes railway.label: Coudekerque-Branche–Fontinettes railway
Coudekerque-Branche–Fontinettes railway.description: The Coudekerque-Branche–Fontinettes railway runs along the English Channel and North Sea coast of France from a junction near Gare de Coudekerque-Branche in Dunkirk to a junction near Gare des Fontinettes in Calais. Wikipedia

Howrah-Bardhaman Chord.label: Howrah–Bardhaman chord
Howrah-Bardhaman Chord.description: The Howrah–Bardhaman chord is a broad-gauge rail line connecting Howrah and Bardhaman. The 95-kilometre long railway line operates in Howrah, Hooghly and Bardhaman districts in the Indian state of West Bengal. Wikipedia

Howrah-New Jalpaiguri Line.label: Howrah–New Jalpaiguri line
Howrah-New Jalpaiguri Line.description: The Howrah–New Jalpaiguri line is a railway line connecting Howrah with New Jalpaiguri railway station in North Bengal in the Indian state of West Bengal. The line continues through North Bengal and southern part of Assam to connect with Guwahati. Wikipedia

Saint-Denis–Dieppe railway.label: Saint-Denis–Dieppe railway
Saint-Denis–Dieppe railway.description: The railway from Saint-Denis to Dieppe is a French 161-kilometre long railway line, that connected Paris to Dieppe on the English Channel coast. It was opened in several stages between 1846 and 1873. Wikipedia

Shijiazhuang–Taiyuan High-Speed Railway.label: Shijiazhuang–Taiyuan High-Speed Railway
Shijiazhuang–Taiyuan High-Speed Railway.description: The Shitai Passenger Railway is a 190-kilometre long high speed railway in China, running from Shijiazhuang to Taiyuan at 250 kilometres per hour. The railway opened on April 1, 2009. Wikipedia

TCDD District 1.label: TCDD District 1
TCDD District 1.description: TCDD District 1 is one of the seven districts of the Turkish State Railways. The headquarters are in Haydarpaşa Terminal in İstanbul. Wikipedia

S3 (Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn).label: S3
S3 (Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn).description: Line S3 is a S-Bahn in the Rhein-Ruhr network. It runs from Oberhausen over Essen to Hattingen Mitte. It is operated at 20 minute intervals, using class 422 four-car electrical multiple units. Wikipedia

Hibiya Line.label: Tokyo Metro Hibiya Line
Hibiya Line.description: The Tokyo Metro Hibiya Line is a subway line in Tokyo, Japan, owned and operated by Tokyo Metro. The line was named after the district of Hibiya, under which it passes. Wikipedia

Toyama Chihō Railway Main Line.label: Toyama Chihō Railway Main Line
Toyama Chihō Railway Main Line.description: The Railway Main Line is a Japanese railway line that connects Dentetsu-Toyama Station in Toyama, Toyama with Unazuki Onsen Station in Kurobe, Toyama. It is owned and run by Toyama Chihō Railway. Wikipedia

Hokuriku Line.label: Hokuriku Main Line
Hokuriku Line.description: The Hokuriku Main Line is a 358.3 kilometer line owned by West Japan Railway Company from Maibara Station in Maibara, Shiga to Naoetsu Station in Jōetsu, Niigata. Wikipedia

Hokushin Line.label: Hokushin Kyūkō Electric Railway
Hokushin Line.description: Hokushin Kyuko Railway Co., Ltd. is a private railway company in Kobe, Japan. Its headquarters are in Kita-ku, Kobe. Investors in the company include Hankyu Railway and Kobe Electric Railway, and it is a subsidiary of Hankyu Hanshin Holdings. Wikipedia

JR Takarazuka Line.label: Fukuchiyama Line
JR Takarazuka Line.description: The Fukuchiyama Line is a railway line operated by West Japan Railway Company between Osaka and Fukuchiyama, Japan. Wikipedia

Midosuji Line.label: Midōsuji Line
Midosuji Line.description: The Midōsuji Line is a rapid transit line in Osaka, Japan, operated by the Osaka Municipal Subway. Constructed under Midōsuji, a major north-south street, it is the oldest line in the Osaka subway ... Wikipedia

JR Kōbe Line.label: JR Kobe Line
JR Kōbe Line.description: The JR Kobe Line is the nickname of portions of the Tōkaidō Main Line and the Sanyō Main Line, between Osaka Station in Osaka, Osaka Prefecture and Himeji Station in Himeji, Hyōgo Prefecture. Wikipedia

Sanyo Shinkansen.label: Sanyō Shinkansen
Sanyo Shinkansen.description: The Sanyō Shinkansen is a line of the Japanese Shinkansen high-speed rail network, connecting Shin-Ōsaka in Osaka with Hakata Station in Fukuoka, the two largest cities in western Japan. Wikipedia

Tōkaidō Line.label: Tōkaidō Main Line
Tōkaidō Line.description: The Tōkaidō Main Line is the busiest trunk line of the Japan Railways Group, connecting Tokyo and Kōbe stations. It is 589.5 km long, not counting its many freight feeder lines around the major cities. Wikipedia

Yūrakuchō Line.label: Tokyo Metro Yūrakuchō Line
Yūrakuchō Line.description: The Tokyo Metro Yūrakuchō Line is a subway line owned and operated by Tokyo Metro. The line connects Wakōshi Station in Wakō, Saitama and Shin-Kiba Station in Kōtō, Tokyo. Wikipedia

Chiyoda Line.label: Tokyo Metro Chiyoda Line
Chiyoda Line.description: The Tokyo Metro Chiyoda Line is a rapid transit line owned and operated by Tokyo Metro in Tokyo, Japan. Wikipedia

Mita Line.label: Toei Mita Line
Mita Line.description: The Toei Mita Line is a subway line of the Tokyo Metropolitan Bureau of Transportation network in Tokyo, Japan. The line runs between Nishi-Takashimadaira in Itabashi and Meguro in Shinagawa. Wikipedia

Narita Sky Access.label: Keisei Narita Airport Line
Narita Sky Access.description: The Keisei Narita Airport Line is a Japanese railway line running between Keisei-Takasago Station and Narita Airport Station. Wikipedia

Mirboo North railway line.label: Mirboo North railway line
Mirboo North railway line.description: The Mirboo North railway line was a country branch line, in Victoria, Australia. The Mirboo North line branched from the main Gippsland line at Morwell station, and opened in 3 stages from 1885 to 1886. Wikipedia

Hankyu Senri Line.label: Hankyū Senri Line
Hankyu Senri Line.description: The Hankyu Senri Line is a railway line in Osaka Prefecture, Japan, operated by Hankyu Railway. It was completed on March 1, 1967. Through trains operate to and from the Hankyu Kyoto Line and the Osaka Municipal Subway Sakaisuji Line. Wikipedia
